%N A002372 Goldbach conjecture: number of decompositions of 2n into ordered sums of two odd primes.
%C A002372 The weak form of this conjecture was proved by Helfgott (see link below). - _T. D. Noe_, May 14 2013
%C A002372 Goldbach conjectured in 1742 that for n >= 3, this sequence never vanishes. This is still unproved.
%C A002372 Number of different primes occurring when 2n is expressed as p1+q1 = ... = pk+qk where pk,qk are odd primes with pk <= qk. For example when n=5: 10 = 3+7 = 5+5, we can see 3 different primes so a(5) = 3. - _Naohiro Nomoto_, Feb 24 2002
%C A002372 Comments from Tomás Oliveira e Silva to Number Theory List, Feb 05 2005: With the help of Siegfied "Zig" Herzog of PSU, I was able to verify the Goldbach conjecture up to 2e17. Let 2n=p+q, with p and q prime be a Goldbach partition of 2n. In a minimal Goldbach partition p is as small as possible. The largest p of a minimal Goldbach partition found was 8443 and is needed for 2n=121005022304007026. Furthermore, the largest prime gap found was 1220-1; it occurs after the prime 80873624627234849.
%C A002372 Comments from Tomás Oliveira e Silva to Number Theory List, Apr 26 2007: With the help of Siegfried "Zig" Herzog, the NCSA and others, I have just finished the verification of the Goldbach conjecture up to 1e18. This took about 320 years of CPU time, including a double-check of the results up to 1e17. As expected, no counterexample to the conjecture was found. As side results, the number of twin primes up to 1e18 was also computed, as was the number of primes in each of the residue classes modulo 120. Also, the number of occurrences of each (observed) prime gap was also recorded.
%C A002372 For n > 2 we have a(n) = 2*A002375(n)-1 if n is prime and a(n) = 2*A002375(n) if n is composite. - _Emeric Deutsch_, Jul 14 2004
%C A002372 For n > 2, a(n) = 2*A002375(n) - A010051(n). - _Jason Kimberley_, Aug 31 2011
%C A002372 a(n) = Sum_{p odd prime < 2*n} A010051(2*n - p). - _Reinhard Zumkeller_, Oct 19 2011
%C A002372 There is an interesting similarity with square numbers: The number of divisors of n is odd iff n is square (A000290).  The number of decompositions of 2n into ordered sums of two primes (equaling the number of the unique primes in all such decompositions) is odd iff n is prime. - _Ivan N. Ianakiev_, Feb 28 2015
